<h2 id="toc8"><span>&quot;Lossy&quot; versus &quot;Lossless&quot;</span></h2>
<p>From Wikipedia:</p>
<blockquote>
<p><em>Lossless data compression is a class of data compression algorithms that allows the exact original data to be reconstructed from the compressed data. The term lossless is in contrast to lossy data compression, which only allows an approximation of the original data to be reconstructed, in exchange for better compression rates.</em></p>
</blockquote>
<p>The short version here is that you want lossless data compression for your raw audio files (the final product to be posted to the main site can be compressed in a lossy format, but ONLY the Mixing Engineer should worry about that, and ONLY for the final product). Lossy runs into the copy-of-a-copy-of-a-copy degradation, which is a BIG problem when you're talking about mixing and remixing tracks over and over (which we are talking about).</p>
<p>There are a bunch of different algorithms which work for lossless compression. For most purposes, .wav files are just fine. Be aware that .mp3 is lossy (which is why it is so much smaller than .wav). So, anything you're forwarding to the Mixing Engineer should be in .wav format.</p>
<hr />
<h1 id="toc9"><span>Troubleshooting</span></h1>
<script type="text/javascript" src="http://d3g0gp89917ko0.cloudfront.net/v--3e3a6f7dbcc9/common--javascript/yahooui/tabview-min.js">
</script>
<div id="wiki-tabview-bf88c07bf7acbf8086346240c4717de8" class="yui-navset">
